    <article class="article PageDW-enJavaScriptReferenceOperatorsCommaOperator" role="main"><div class="page-title hideforedit">&#13;
              <h1 class="first entry-title roundTop" id="title">Comma Operator</h1>            &#13;
      &#13;
              </div>&#13;
      &#13;
    <div class="page-content boxed">&#13;
&#13;
     &#13;
       &#13;
    &#13;
            &#13;
      <div id="page-top"><div class="pageText" id="pageText">
<div id="section_1"><span id="Summary"/><h2 class="editable">Summary</h2>
<p>The comma operator evaluates both of its operands (from left to right) and returns the value of the second operand.</p>
<table class="standard-table"><tbody><tr><td colspan="2" class="header">Operator</td> </tr><tr><td>Implemented in:</td> <td>JavaScript 1.0</td> </tr><tr><td>ECMA Version:</td> <td>ECMA-262</td> </tr></tbody></table></div><div id="section_2"><span id="Syntax"/><h2 class="editable">Syntax</h2>
<p><code> <em>expr1</em>, <em>expr2</em> </code></p>
</div><div id="section_3"><span id="Parameters"/><h2 class="editable">Parameters</h2>
<dl><dt><code>expr1</code>, <code>expr2</code> </dt> <dd>Any expressions.</dd>
</dl></div><div id="section_4"><span id="Description"/><h2 class="editable">Description</h2>
<p>You can use the comma operator when you want to include multiple expressions in a location that requires a single expression. The most common usage of this operator is to supply multiple parameters in a <code>for</code> loop.</p>
</div><div id="section_5"><span id="Example"/><h2 class="editable">Example</h2>
<p>If <code>a</code> is a 2-dimensional array with 10 elements on a side, the following code uses the comma operator to increment two variables at once. The code prints the values of the diagonal elements in the array:</p>
&#13;
          <pre name="code" class="js">for (var i = 0, j = 9; i &lt;= 9; i++, j--)
  document.writeln("a[" + i + "][" + j + "] = " + a[i][j]);</pre>&#13;
        
<p/></div></div></div>&#13;
